Title : Harrison Richardson
Text : '''Harrison L. Richardson''' (1930 - February 26, 2009) was an American lawyer and politician from [[Maine]]. A [[Maine Republican Party|Republican]], Richardson served three terms in the [[Maine House of Representatives]] (1965-1971) and one term in the [[Maine Senate]] (1973â€“75). He represented [[Cumberland, Maine|Cumberland]] in the Legislature.<ref name="obit">{{cite web|url=http://obituaries.pressherald.com/obituaries/mainetoday-pressherald/obituary.aspx?n=harrison-l-richardson&pid=124725577|title=Harrison L. Richardson Obituary|date=March 1, 2009|publisher=[[Portland Press Herald]]|accessdate=28 April 2014}}</ref>

==Political career==
Richardson was a proponent of Maine's first income tax, which was adopted in 1969 due to a crisis in funding mental health. He was also an early advocate of [[container deposit legislation]], which was eventually adopted by the State in 1978. During his final two terms in the House, Richardson served as the Majority Leader. He unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination for [[Governor of Maine]] in [[1974 Maine gubernatorial election|1974]], losing to [[James Erwin (politician)|James Erwin]]. He also served two terms on the [[University of Maine]] Board of Trustees. He was also a trustee at [[Maine Maritime Academy]] and the [[American University in Bulgaria]].<ref name="obit"/>

==Professional career==
A well-known trial lawyer, Richardson was named a Fellow to the [[American College of Trial Lawyers]] in 1975.<ref name="obit"/>

==Personal==
Richardson played with the [[University of Maine]] [[Maine Black Bears football|football team]], where was an All-New England tackle. He served in the [[United States Marine Corps]], including 14 months in [[Korean War|Korea]]. He died on February 26, 2009 at his home in [[Gorham, Maine|Gorham]].<ref name="obit"/>

